<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="36b81426-c906-5870-82d6-7cc5446c2875" activityNameId="687c7b57-c372-463d-a9e1-7ab2ecc27764" parentActivityId="50bd1f29-0584-5078-ac0b-291d82f07784" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">phosphane production</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Phosphorus trihydride</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">White Phosphorus</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Red phosphorus</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Phosphane</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">PHOSPHINE</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">PHOSPHORUS</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">From the reception of phosphorus, pure water and sodium hydroxide at the factory gate.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">This activity ends with the production of phosphane including the consumption of raw materials, energy uses, infrastructure and emissions. Since phosphane is a very poisonous gas, the whole system is a closed loop. Therefore no emissions to air are considered.

</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of phosphane by means of the hydration of phosphorus. Phosphane is a colorless, very poisonous gas whith an intense and penetrating odor.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">It is mostly used captively as a starting material in the production of organophosphorus compounds, mainly by addition of aldehydes or alkenes to the P–H bonds. Phosphane is also used for pest control where foodstuffs and animal feeds are stored. Almost all dry products of this type are suitable for gassing with phosphane without any harmful effects on properties such as smell, taste, and appearance. The main area of use is in gassing grain silos. In the semiconductor industry, specially purified phosphane (arsine-free in particular) is used as a dopant.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Due to a lack of industrial data, this dataset is based on stoechiometric calculations and approximations based on data from a large chemical plant (Gendorf 2016).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Sutter, J. (2007) Life Cycle Inventories of Highly Pure Chemicals. ecoinvent report No. 19. Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, 2007.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Bettermann, G., Krause, W., Riess, G. and Hofmann, T. 2000. Phosphorus Compounds, Inorganic. Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Gendorf (2016) Umwelterklärung 2015, Werk Gendorf Industriepark, www.gendorf.de.</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="8a45a80b-336f-4a04-95fb-1a1be360d2d3">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2021:Manufacture of pesticides and other agrochemical products</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="34dbbff8-88ce-11de-ad60-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">GLO</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The inventory is modelled for the world. Some values are based on data from a large chemical factory located in Germany. These are assumed to be valid for this geography.</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Phosphane can be synthesized by a number of different reactions. On the laboratory scale, it may be prepared simply by the hydrolysis of metal phosphides or phosphonium salts. The two most common industrial methods are based on disproportionation reactions of elemental phosphorus catalyzed by alkalies or acids. A well-known example is the reaction of white phosphorus with sodium hydroxide solution, which is used to produce both phosphane and sodium hypophosphite, NaH2PO2 (sodium phosphinite).</text>
          <imageUrl index="1">https://db3.ecoinvent.org/images/3f4eaf62-4660-4860-82e8-14f3ba8e8cef</imageUrl>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">In sodium hypophosphite production plants, the phosphane byproduct is usually burnt off. In the presence of alcohols, the reaction may be controlled such that the product formed in addition to phosphane is almost entirely sodium phosphite Na2HPO3. At the same time, the maximum yield based on the amount of phosphorus used increases from 25 % to 50 %. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">In acid-catalyzed disproportionation, white phosphorus is converted into phosphane and phosphoric acid at ca. 280 °C, red phosphorus being formed as an intermediate.</text>
          <imageUrl index="4">https://db3.ecoinvent.org/images/e7b96b0f-ab70-43a9-ad84-7a7523ad8850</imageUrl>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">This reaction gives the highest yield of PH3 based on the amount of phosphorus used (theoretical yield 62.5 % for phosphane and 37.5 % for phosphoric acid). Due to the high reaction temperature and the corrosiveness of the medium, the reactor must be made of graphite.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">The phosphoric acid is then neutralized with sodium hydroxide.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">In this dataset, the production of phosphane by means of the hydration of phosphorus is considered.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">Svara, J., Weferling, N.: Phosphorus compounds, organic. Published online: 2000. In: Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Seventh Edition, 2004 Electronic Release (ed. Fiedler E., Grossmann G., Kersebohm D., Weiss G. and Witte C.). 7 th Electronic Release Edition. Wiley InterScience, New York, Online-Version under: http://www.mrw.interscience.wiley.com/emrw/9783527306732/home</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2000-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Time of publications. Some values are based on data published by the Gendorf factory that were collected between 2011 and 2015. The time period has been adjusted accordingly. For more details, see the comments of the exchanges.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
    <flowData>
      <intermediateExchange id="8b949796-b86c-5ea4-92c6-214cc8fbe720" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" variableName="RP" casNumber="7803-51-2" amount="1.0" intermediateExchangeId="55c9955a-88d5-4954-9703-b7db1d7d04d6" productionVolumeAmount="34770.1149425287" productionVolumeVariableName="RP_PV">
        <name xml:lang="en">phosphane</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Phosphane is is a colorless, very poisonous gas whith an intense and penetrating odor. The odor threshold is extremely dependent on the purity of the gas. High-purity PH3 (5 N), as used in the semiconductor industry, is detectable by smell only when the concentration is at a dangerously toxic level (&gt; 1000 ppm), but when PH3 is produced by the hydrolysis of AlP or Mg3P2, it can be detected even at ca. 20 ppb. Phosphane is very toxic. The LC50 and LD50 values show that the acute toxicity decreases with increasing molecular mass. Above 375 °C, phosphine decomposes into the elements. Phosphine - air mixtures are explosive over a wide range. The lower explosion limit is 1.6%, and the upper limit is close to 100 %. Pure phosphine should presumably therefore be regarded as spontaneously flammable like phosphine that contains P2H4 as an impurity. With strong acids, phosphine forms phosphonium salts; e.g., with hydrogen iodide, phosphonium iodide, PH4I, is formed, from which pure phosphine may be liberated by adding water or solutions of alkalimetal hydroxides.

The phosphane is mostly used captively as a starting material in the production of organophosphorus compounds, mainly by addition of aldehydes or alkenes to the P-H bonds. Phosphine is also used for pest control where foodstuffs and animal feeds are stored. Almost all dry products of this type are suitable for gassing with phosphane without any harmful effects on such properties as smell, taste, and appearance. The main area of use is in gassing grain silos. In the semiconductor industry, specially purified phosphane (arsine-free in particular) is used as a dopant.</comment>
